ergence whereby rightist politicians likeSarkozy and Cameron join hands with some leftist intellectuals like BennMichaels, Žižek, and Bourdieu in condemning "multiculturalism" and "identitypolitics." At once a report from various "fronts" in the culture wars, amapping of the germane literatures, and an argument about methods of readingthe cross-border movement of ideas, the book constitutes a major contribution toour understanding of the Diasporic and the Transnational.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-SA 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/4.0  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aCulture. 0aEthnicityzAtlantic Ocean Region. 0aMulticulturalismzAtlantic Ocean Region. 0aPostcolonialismzAtlantic Ocean Region. 0aRace. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh1 aStam, Robert, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertNew York University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311070644440uhttps://doi.org/10.18574/nyu/9780814798379.001.0001zOpen Access7040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780814723920zOpen Access70423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780814723920/original  a978-3-11-070644-4 New York University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-GOA